{"id":18953,"date":"2025-04-14T14:40:03","date_gmt":"2025-04-14T12:40:03","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/?p=18953"},"modified":"2025-04-14T20:16:14","modified_gmt":"2025-04-14T18:16:14","slug":"africa-boosting-infrastruture-to-attract-investment","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/africa-boosting-infrastruture-to-attract-investment\/","title":{"rendered":"AFRICA boosting infrastruture to attract investment."},"content":{"rendered":"<p><img fetchpriority=\"high\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-18954 alignleft\" src=\"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/04\/WAMKELE-3-300x169.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" \/><\/p>\n<p><strong>Story by George Sanzila<\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>Date: 13 April 2025<\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>Antalya, Turkey &#8211;<\/strong> The Secretary General of the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA), Wamkele Mene says Africa has begun to fast track the development of its infrastructure alongside harmonised trade regulations to attract investment and accelerate the continent\u2019s economic development. Wamkele said this during a panel discussion titled \u201cConnecting Africa: A prospect for continental integration\u201d, at the 4th Antalya Diplomacy Forum in Turkey.<\/p>\n<p>The AfCFTA, one of the flagship projects of the African Union\u2019s Agenda 2063, is a single market trade agreement that removes trade barriers by creating the free flow of goods and services and facilitating investment and the movement of people and capital throughout Africa.<\/p>\n<p>According to Wamkele, the AfCFTA has been immersed in mobilising development finance to ensure that Africa readies itself. \u201cWe are mobilising finance to build infrastructure that supports trade. Over the last five years, the African Development Bank has invested over 40 billion dollars. Since it\u2019s establishment, the AFREXIM Bank has invested over 20 billion dollars. It is ofcourse not enough, so we have to mobilise more investment\u201d, noted the Secretary General.<\/p>\n<p>He further stated that a harmonised regulatory framework has the potential to mitigate confusion and ease investor decisions. \u201cThe rules that we have developed, establishes a harmonised integrated market, which is the starting point. Investors want to see whether you have rules that create a single market and rules that enable the resolution of disputes in a prescribed manner. These rules give investors confidence and are considered when investors look for invetment opportunities\u201d, noted Wamkele.<\/p>\n<p>Wamkele revealed during the discussion that Africa heads of State recently adopted a protocol on digital trade, a first of its kind in the world, which creates a single market for Africa\u2019s digital economy. This comes against the backdrop of the continent\u2019s projected digital economy growing to over 720 billion dollars by the year 2050, according to the International Finance Corporation. Digital economy refers to economic activities generated from the use of digital technology.<\/p>\n<p>Wamkele stated that this will create endless opportunities, particularly to small and medium sized businesses and the youth. \u201cThis will create opportubnities for young people that are innovative in the digital economy and will enable seamless payments across the continent and the movement of data\u201d, said Wamkele.<\/p>\n<p>Ugandan foreign affairs Minister, Jeje abubakhar Odongo told delegates that the continent\u2019s integration agenda has taken centre stage. \u201cFor us integration comes a long way. Regional economic blocks are seen as building blocks for the process of integration of the entire continent. They are seen as transitory and are not an end in themselves as far as integration is concerned\u201d, said Odongo.<\/p>\n<p>The forum, hosted by Turkey\u2019s foreign affairs ministry under the auspices of President Recep Tayyip Erdogan attacted hundreds of delegates including heads of state, ministers, academics, diplomats and members of parliament among others, to re-evaluate diplomacy and find solutions to pertinent issues affecting the world. It was held under the theme \u201cReclaiming Diplomacy in a Fragmented world\u201d.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Story by George Sanzila Date: 13 April 2025 Antalya, Turkey &#8211; The Secretary General of the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA), Wamkele Mene says Africa has begun to fast track the development of its infrastructure alongside harmonised trade regulations to attract investment and accelerate the continent\u2019s economic development. Wamkele said this during a panel&hellip;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":16,"featured_media":18957,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[159,39],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-18953","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-home-page-slider","category-news","category-159","category-39","description-off"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/18953","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/16"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=18953"}],"version-history":[{"count":1,"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/18953\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":18955,"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/18953\/revisions\/18955"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/18957"}],"wp:attachm